building forrnerlx\noccupied by Todd, Barrow Co.\n(Texas Realty Company). \u039b first\nclass fire-proof vault and other ad\nvantages goes with the office. Terms\nreasonable. See W. G. McClain oi\nWill Hancock. ti\nSenior II. V. I*. TT. Program.\nTopic: Christian Growth. Leader,\nMr. J. S. Herring.\nScripture, 2 Peter, 1st chapter.\nGod's promise for our growth. 2d\nPeter, 1:1-4. Mr. Frank Dennington.\nGraces to be added. 2 Peter, 1:5-7.\nMrs. Baird. Result of Growth. 2 Pe\nter, 1:7-10. Mrs. Ernest Miller.\nWarning and exhortation to those\nwho know God's will. 2 Peter, 3:17\n18, Miss Marie Kemble.\n\u03bf\n\ni oi:i:< \\st \u03ba\u03bf\u03ba \u03bd\u03ba.\u03c7\u03c4 u \u03ba\u03b9 \u03ba\n\n00\nNow Vol l<. Jan. 4. \u0393\u00b7.\u03c4\u03cb\u00b7 will\nreassemble Monday ;.nd the senators j\nI iliiil representatives. refreshed by a\nI period of holiday cheer, will enter i\nupon the real work of thu session j\nwith renewed vim. It is likely that\nthe reopening of congress will be\ntaken advantage of by the friends\nand supporters of Speaker Joseph\nCannon to formally announce his j\ncandidacy for the republican presi- i\ndentiai nomination. Scores of con\ngres: men favor Cannon and the\nlaunching of the boom will be at\ntended by considerable enthusiasm.\nPractically all of the republican\nmembers of the house who have not\nfavorite sons in their own states are\nsolidly back of the speaker.\nInharmonious conditions in the\nnavy department, which led to the\nresignation of Rear Admiral Wil\nlard H. Bronson from the office of\nchief of the naval bureau of naviga\ntion, will likely receive the atten\nI tion of both houses during the com\nj ing wee. The resignation of Bronson\nfollowing close on the heels of Hen\nry Reuterdahl's attack on the bur\nI eau system of the navy department,\nl has revealed the strife existing in\nj the conduct of the navy and the\nneed for a more harmonious admin\nI istration.\nAdditional railroad legislation has\nJ also been demanded by many im\nI portant organizations, and several\nI resolutions on this subject will be\nj placed before the solons when they\nI gather on Monday. It is the general\nsentiment of congressmen, however,\nI that the time is not opportune for\nthe passage of bills of this character.\nThaw Trial Again.\nThe trial of Harry Kendall Thaw\nfor the murder of Stanford White \u03b9\nis set for Moifcttj\u00b7, before Justj<^\nVictor .1. ntiwmg in \"the origin*\nbranch of the supreme court in New\nYork city. It is expected that there\nwill be little delay and that the \u03b9\nwork of securing a jury will be com\nmenced almost immediately and be\ncontinued, with day and night ses\nsions, until completed. District At\ntorney Jerome will again conduct\nI the prosecution, and Thaw will be I\nj defended by Martin W. Littleton,\nassisted by several other prominent\nI attorneys. Insanity will be the plea\nI of the defendant, according to the\nI present plans of the defense.\nStandard Oil uses.\nThe hearing before Judge Frank\ni lin Ferris iu the government's suit\nto dissolve the Standard Oil com\npany of New Jersey, the $100,000,\n000 parent concern of the \"oil\ntrust,\" will be resumed in New York\nI Monday. A mass of testimony which\nhas been given in other suits against\nthe Standard will be introduced.\nKlkilis I jaw Te*\u00a3\nAttorney General Bonaparte will\nprobably make his first appearance\nin the United States supreme court\nas the government's chief law offi\ni cer on Monday, frhen the rebate\ncase against the Great Northern, in\nwhich the railroad company is un\nder sentence to pay a fine of $15,\n000, is to be argued.\nTwo-Cent Fare fjaw\nAnother case involving the pow\ner of the federal courts to interfere\nin the execution of state railroad\nrate laws will be taken up by the\nUnited States supreme court on Mon\nday, when the federal judges for the\ndistrict of Nebraska are ordered to\nappear and show cause why a writ\nof mandamus, asked for by the state\nofficials of Nebraska to prevent in\nterference with the enforcement of\nthe two-cent fare law, should not\nissue.\nReturn of Prosperity.\nIt is estimated that not less than\n100,000 men, who have been idle\nfor several weeks owing to the shut\ndown of plants in the great indus\ntrial centers of the country, will re\nturn to work, Jn the steel mills and\nfactories of the Pittsburg district\nalone about 40,000 men will share\nin the returning prosperity. In\nCleveland at least 10,000 men will\ni resume work at their former occu\n1\nI pations, and hundreds of great fac\ntories and mills in other cities will\nbe\u00a3ni operations on Monday.\nPolitical I'ow-Wows.\nWilliam Jennings Bryan will be\nindorsed as the democratic candidate\ni for the presidency at the state eon\n1\nveption of the New York Progres\nsive Democratic league to be held\nin Cooper Union, New York. 0:1\nTuesday. On th<\u00b7 same d. 1 King'\nCounty Republican committee will\nmeet in Brooklyn, when the fight\nfor and against the indorsement of i\nGovernor Hughes for the presidency\nwill be brought to a climax.\nNew Battleship Heady.\nThe new battleship Idaho, first\nof the three new war vessels to be\ncompleted, is expected to be ready\nfor sea duty next, week, while the\nMississippi and the New Hampshire\nwill be ready in the spring.\nlirnzil to Greet Fleet.\nAmerica's armada under Admiral\nEvans is due to reach Rio de Janiei\nro. Brazil, next Saturday and will\nspend ten days at that port The\nfleet will be met by a squadron of\nBrazilian naval vessels and escorted\ninto the harbor of Rio with great\npomp and ceremony.\nCotton Crop Reduction.\nDiscussion of a proposition to re\nduce the cotton arcreage throughout\nthe south this wear will be the prin\ncipal matter before the convention\nof the Farmers' Educational and\nCo-operative union, to open in Mem\nphis, Tenn., on Tuesday. Another\nimportant, convention to be held in\nthe south next week will be that of\nthe National League of Commission\nMerchants, which opens in Savan\nnah, Ga., on Wednesday.\nFairbanks and Roosevelt.\nVice President and Mrs. Fair\nbanks will give their annual dinner\nin honor of President and Mrs.\nRoosevelt at their Washington resi\ndence on Tuesday night.\nTill. SHAKKSI'KARK (M l>.\nQuestions on the Lesson for tlie\nMeeting January 7.\nFollow are the questions on the\nlesson for the meeting of the\nShakespeare Club, January 7:\nLesson, Act 4, Scenes 1, 2 and 3. \u03b9\nAnswer roll call with quotations.\nScene 1.\nWhat departure from history does\nthis scene begin with?\nWhat was Antony's opinion of\nLepidus?\nWhat was his object in retaining\nhim?\nTo what does he compare Lepidus?\nWhat fact, does Antony bring out J\nconcerning Brutus and Cassius,\nWhy do they raise an army?\nExplain \"million of mischief?\"\nWhat insight in the stato of af\nfairs does this scene give?\nScene 2.\nWhere is the scene now shifted?\nWhat is meant by \"to wish things\nundone?\"\nAccording to Brutus what is the\nsign of \"cooling friendship?\"\nWhat hint is given in this scene\nabout Brutus and Cassius?\nScene 3.\nWhat complaint does Cassius\nmake?\nMeaning of reply of Brutus?\nWhat accusation does he bring\nagainst Cassius?\nGive the quarrel in your own\nwords?\nWhat is thought of the way\nShakespeare handled this quarrel?\nHow does ^rutus show his integ\nrity?\nWhat lovely thought does he give\nabout friends?\nWas Antony's great show of grief\nat Brutus' anger, acting or real?\nHow is Brutus affected by it?\nWhy does Cassius claim that h\u00b7\ngot his \"rash humor\" from his mo\nther?\nWhat lines prove that the soldiers\nsuspect the generals are quarreling?\nDescribe the poet's efforts at\npeacemaking?\nWhy do they wish to conceal the\nquarrel?\nWhat cause had Brutus for losing\nhis hold on stoicism?\nHow did Portia die?\nDo Plutarch and other writers\nsupport Shakespeare in this account\nof her death?\nWhat Is thought fom the corres\npondence of Cicero?\nDo you think her tragic end in\nharmony with her character?\nWhat seems lacking in Cassius\nthat he dwells so much on Portia's\ndeath?\nAccount for Brutus' manner when\nMessala tells him of Portia's death?\nDoes Cassius think him unfeeling?\nBrutus' reason for proposing to\nmarch to Phillippi and how does\nCassius meet it?\nGive ihe lines commencing\n\"There is a tide,\" etc.?\nDid Cassius yield to Brutus be\ncause he was convinced? Why then1\nHow is the disturbed m'nd of\nBrutus intimated?\nDescribe the entrance of Cassius'\nghost?\nDid Brutus receive this as a warn\ning?\nOf what was the ghost a symbol?\nWhy should it appear to Brutus\nand not to the other conspirators?\nWere not the others more guiuy?\nWas the spirit of Caesar destroy\ned when his body was killed?\nShow how it lived after his death?\nHow does Brutus invariably speak\nof Caesar?\nWhat then did he resent in him?\nHow was it different with Cas\nsius?\nSpeciil ri'lestions assigned as fol\nlows:\nWhen r.ud how is Julius Caesar\nmentioned elsewhce in Shakespeare\nMiss McDuffie.\nCompare the mob in this play\nwith the one in Corilanus.\u2014Miss\nMoore.\nThe two wives of the play.\u2014Mrs.\nBertram.\nJ. C. Lumpkins has moved his law\noffices from over Matthews Broth\ners' store to the rooms formerly oc\ncupied by Farrar Pieson over the\nWaxahachie National bank.\nCure* Tetter,\nEczema, Itch (all\nkinds) Dew Poison,\nPimples, Ring,\nworm. Skin\nEruptions, Chap\nped Face\u00b7 and\nHands, Sore,\nSweatty, Swollen,\nBlistered Feet.\nCotton Picker\u00b7\nPick y4\nMore\nCotton by\nUsing It\nDONT SCRATCH|\nHQ0P[R5TtTT[fii\nm.\nCURES\n.ISKIR!\nIAND\n[FOOT ANDl\n'SCALP\nr-TROUBLEs!\nDEATH TO\nRED BUG\n|\u00f4urcguRE\n\"Mjrr\nCITY DRIC\n'\u039b hen your hands crack open\nand bleed, use 'Hooper's Tet\nCure.\"\nDandruff is a germ disease\n\"Hooper's Tetter Cure\" is\ngreatest germ destroyer knowi\nIn winter time \"Tetter a\nzema\" begin to trouble\nDon't forget \"Hooper's 1\nCure.\"\nStanding on the feet ci\nto blister, sweat, swell, ac\u00c7\nbecome tender, \u2014\"Hooper'J\nter Cure